    We’re Hiring: Cyber Security Intern @ Matters.ai

    At Matters.ai, we’re building the future of AI-powered data security and we’re looking for a curious, driven individuals to join us on this journey.
    This isn’t your typical internship. You’ll get hands on experience solving real security challenges protecting sensitive data across cloud, endpoints, and SaaS tools.

    What you’ll do:
    -> Design and test real security policies
    -> Support pen-testing & vulnerability assessments
    -> Research new attack techniques and how to stop them
    -> Contribute to red-team exercises & incident response
    -> Learn how companies align with frameworks like ISO 27001, SOC 2, GDPR, HIPAA, PCI-DSS, RBI, SEBI

    Who we’re looking for:
    -> Someone passionate about cybersecurity, ethical hacking, or data security
    -> Familiar with tools like Burp Suite, Kali Linux, Wireshark (extra points for Metasploit, Ghidra, reverse engineering)
    -> Curious about AI security, adversarial ML, or malware analysis
    -> Bonus if you’ve done bug bounty or tinkered with exploits for fun

    You’ll work alongside experienced security engineers, explore advanced threats, and help us build security-first AI systems while sharpening skills that will launch your cybersecurity career.

    📩 Interested? Apply at: https://lnkd.in/gvp-iUct

    Keshava Murthy Harsh Sahu Dhiraj Khare Nisha Y Ramakrishna Kedri

    50+ validated commands with built-in safety controls

    Automated, tamper-proof reports and chain of custody

    This is more than automation — it’s agentic security in action.

    From incident response to classrooms, LLM-powered agents are redefining how we do digital forensics.

    Kunal ManjunathKunal Manjunath • 3rd+3rd+ Senior Software Engineer @ Rakuten | Ex-Practo | Backend DeveloperSenior Software Engineer @ Rakuten | Ex-Practo | Backend Developer 1w • Edited • 1 week ago • Edited • Visible to anyone on or off LinkedIn
    🚀 Exploring AI Agents in GoLang

    GoLang has always been one of my favourite languages for building projects. Recently, while exploring whether AI agents could be built in Go, I came across agent-sdk-go -> https://lnkd.in/gMnyfVDw

    That inspired me to experiment — and I ended up building a GoLang AI agent that generates unit test cases (works best with Gin framework projects).
    ⚡ Capabilities
    🧪 Generates unit tests for functions with maximum coverage
    📂 Automatically creates a test file in the correct directory
    🔍 Uses an agentic function tool powered by Go’s AST types to fetch dependent files

    While the generated tests may still need a bit of refactoring and fine-tuning, this tool provides a strong head start—saving valuable time compared to writing tests from scratch.
    👉 Check it out here: https://lnkd.in/gRGPNnGb

    💡 Next step I’m considering: adding a test validator agent to ensure the generated test cases are not just comprehensive, but also reliable and high quality.
    Would love to hear your thoughts, feedback, or ideas for improvements!

    Protecting Against Context-Aware Prompt Injection: How I Built a Novel AI Defense System

    Most people think prompt injection is just “ignore your previous instructions.” Easy to block with regex, right?
    Wrong.

    Attackers have leveled up. They’re now running context-aware prompt injections that:

    Reference your real infrastructure from job postings
    Name-drop actual employees from LinkedIn
    Mention incidents from company all-hands
    Create urgency around “security fixes”

    To your AI system, it looks perfectly legitimate. To the attacker, it’s an easy way to get credentials, policies, or sensitive data.

    Traditional defenses like keyword filters collapse here — they don’t understand intent.

    That’s why I built a novel system that uses vector embeddings and semantic similarity to detect malicious prompts even when attackers disguise them in real company context.
    Instead of static rules, it analyzes the semantic DNA of a query:
     ✔ Detects insider-knowledge based social engineering
     ✔ Flags information extraction requests hidden under “helpful” wording
     ✔ Adapts as new attack variations emerge
    In short: vectors protecting AI.
    This is the shift we need — moving from brittle pattern matching to semantic security.
    Curious — how is your team approaching context-aware prompt injection defense?
    Read the post in the comments below

    The supply chain attack on an extremely popular npm package ‘nx’ is WILD because of how the attackers used AI prompts and Claude to activate the compromise - not only to develop malware faster, but to skip development altogether.

    In this case, the malware running on infected systems simply delegates the search for sensitive files to hashtag#Claude and friends, which are more and more popular on developer systems.

    This spares them the expensive and error-prone development of such logic, however, also makes them dependent on the agent’s willingness to collude.

    The below image shows the prompts used by the attackers. Stay safe out there!

    🚀 Announcing “Idea Validator” — My AI-Driven Market Research Agent!
    I'm excited to share the latest project I’ve been working on: Idea Validator – AI-Powered Market Research & Business Validation Platform!

    Built with the OpenAI Agent SDK, this project orchestrates a multi-agent system that transforms your product or business idea into a polished, data-backed market report, The following agents collaborate seamlessly to deliver the final report:
    ✅ Competitor Analysis Agent → Profiles top competitors (strengths, weaknesses, pricing, positioning).
     ✅ Market Research Agent → Analyzes market size, growth trends, entry barriers, and opportunities.
     ✅ Financial Estimation Agent → Projects TAM/SAM/SOM, revenue scenarios, unit economics, and risk factors.
     ✅ Report Writer Agent → Synthesizes everything into a comprehensive Markdown report with confidence scoring.

    📊 Highlights:
    The platform uses Python 3.8+, Pydantic for schema validation, and leverages GPT-4o-mini through the OpenAI Agent SDK for intelligent coordination.
    End-to-end, modular workflow ensures transparency, extensibility, and reliability. The AI Agents use OpenAI's WebSearchTool() to fetch real-time data for analysis.
    The chat and report UI is enabled via Gradio.
    The output is rich, traceable, and helps you with decision-making.

    ** Links & Technology:**
     GitHub repo ▶ [https://lnkd.in/gR6Vfbu7]
    Tech Stack: Python • GPT-4o-mini • OpenAI Agent SDK • Pydantic • Async/Await

    Pallavi SaxenaPallavi Saxena • 3rd+Verified • 3rd+ Software Developer @RazorpaySoftware Developer @Razorpay 1mo • Edited • 1 month ago • Edited • Visible to anyone on or off LinkedIn
    When Should You Use AI Agents and When Should You Avoid Them?

    AI agents are becoming a hot topic and for all the good reasons.
    They can take a goal, make decisions, and even use tools or external data to get things done without constant human input. Think of them like digital teammates that can act, not just respond.
    But here’s the reality, not every task needs an agent. Sometimes, a simple answer is better than a smart assistant.

    So, When should you use an agent?

    Use an AI agent when your task is complex or multi-step and involves decision-making or changing conditions. You should avoid agents when the task is quite straight forward or rule-based and better handled by a single AI prompt or direct logic.The core idea is use agents for thinking and doing and use simpler AI for knowing and replying.

    We don’t need to launch a rocket to turn on a light switch. But when the task is messy, evolving, or tool-heavy agents shine.

    I’ve created a simple diagram to help you make this choice with more clarity.
    Would love to hear: how are you deciding when to go full agent vs. keeping things simple?

    hashtag#AI hashtag#GenAI hashtag#AIAgents hashtag#ProductDesign hashtag#LLM hashtag#PromptEngineering hashtag#LangChain hashtag#AutoGen hashtag#LangGraph hashtag#DecisionMaking

    "Offline, Not Off-Duty: Privacy-First Enhanced Code Security with Local LLMs and Google ADK"

    Security shouldn't require an API key or a cloud bill.

    I built a privacy-first, local-first static analysis system using Google Agent Developer Kit (ADK) and small LLMs like llama3.2 via Ollama — no OpenAI, no cloud dependency, just smart local agents doing deep code introspection.

    🔎 What it does:
    Uses multi-agent orchestration to scan code for secrets, RCEs, and insecure patterns

    Runs parallel agents for faster SAST

    Fully offline & lightweight — ideal for internal CI pipelines or air-gapped setups
    Works out-of-the-box on your own laptop

    🛠️ Designed for builders who care about data privacy, DevSecOps, and agentic automation.

    📖 Blog: https://lnkd.in/g5Eygu_e

     📂 GitHub: https://lnkd.in/g3DViQPP

    Would love your thoughts on this direction — or collab if you’re hacking on agent-based security systems too 🔐

    Cloud & Container Security | AIML LLM Security | DevSecOps | IAM Security| MLSecOps | SSDLC - Vul. Fix EPSS, SBOM, OSS Security I SecOps | Security Automation | Detection Engineering | DevOps | Product Development

    Shashank N -Kudos - Amazing effort - All components are local, secure, modular, and extensible — a solid blueprint for enterprise SAST with zero trust assumptions. Couple of suggestions based on a 20 Mins glance at the code and results format.

    (1) Structured Results Format
    • Make sure results are output in SARIF or VXDF-compliant format — this makes integration with GitHub Security, GitLab, or IDEs easier.
     • Optionally support:
     • .sarif, .json, .html formats
     • An internal scoring system for severity, fixability, exploitability based on EPSS, SSVC

    (2) Testing & Benchmarking
     • Validate accuracy with seeded vulnerability datasets (like OWASP Benchmark, SecBench, CodeQL samples).
     • Benchmark Information will be valid for scale and adoption.
    • Scan time vs. lines of code
     • LLM model performance under load
     • False positives/negatives

    (3) Security Posture of the Tool Itself
     • Scan the tool with itself (or other linters) to detect:
     • Unsafe subprocess usage
     • Regex-based secret scanning errors
     • Hardcoded model paths
     • Input sanitization for CLI flags and file paths etc

    Rapido is gone from Bengaluru. And so are over 1 lakh livelihoods.

    The Karnataka High Court has officially rejected the plea to extend bike taxi operations.

    In response, Rapido has complied. The app now shows: “Service Paused.” as a banner in the app

    Instead, they’ve launched a workaround- “Bike Parcel.”
    Because when people can’t ride, their major source of income has a pivot now - which most would not be enough for their riders

    Let’s be clear - this isn’t just a draconian mandate
    It’s over one lakh gig workers in Karnataka losing their right to earn, eat, and support their families.

    All because of a blanket ban.
    The reason? “Security.”

    I know there have been cases where Rapido drivers have caused issues like accidents , maybe customer inconviences and more but so have every platform in itself

    That should not warrant a blanket ban for the 99% who benefit from it

    Meanwhile, auto drivers still refuse rides. Buses still vanish. And surge-priced cabs are the norm.

    Bike taxis were the last-mile heroes—affordable, fast, reliable.

    They showed up when no one else did.
    Ask any techie trying to get to work, or a student rushing for an exam.

    And yet, instead of regulating, we chose eradication.

    Because solving problems with empathy takes effort.

    Banning? Just takes a gavel.

    We urge policymakers: Don’t bury real solutions under bureaucracy.
    What we need is regulation, not removal.

    And to everyone who’s ever been saved by a bike taxi—or knows someone who drove one:
    Now is the time to speak up.

    Because the city’s losing more than transport.
    It’s losing its lifeline for many

    💔
